[head=1]CIRO'S GUIDE TO BRIGMED[/head]
[head=2]Subject: How to Patch Everything and Don't Die Trying[/head]
[head=3]By: Ciro Volkoville Malet[/head]
───────────────────────────────────────

This document defines the priority-based chemical production order for Brig Medical operations.  
Focus: rapid treatment of the most frequent damage types using minimal, reliable recipes.  
Optimization is secondary to speed, availability, and ChemMaster workflow stability.

───────────────────────────────────────
[head=3]CORE MEDICATIONS (HIGH PRIORITY)[/head]

[color=#ffaa00][bold]WOUNDGLUE[/bold][/color] — Brute Damage | Dose: 15u  
- Reagents: [bold]Oxygen (1) | Sugar (1) | Carbon (4)[/bold]  
- Notes: Continuous production; keep at top of ChemMaster

[color=#731024][bold]CRITPACK[/bold][/color] — Critical Asphyxiation | Dose: 20u  
- Reagents: [bold]Oxygen (1) | Sugar (1) | Carbon (1)[/bold]  
- Notes: Speed prioritized over optimization

[color=#215263][bold]FIRE FOR DUMMIES[/bold][/color] — Burns | Dose: 10u  
- Reagents: [bold]Silicon (1) | Carbon (1) | Oxygen (2) | Phosphorus (2)[/bold]

[color=#3a1d8a][bold]POISONOFF[/bold][/color] — Poison / Toxins | Dose: 20u  
- Reagents: [bold]Silicon (1) | Nitrogen (1) | Potassium (1)[/bold]

[color=#00e5ff][bold]CRY AWAY[/bold][/color] - Always have some in case people get minor boo boos
Reagents: [bold] Inaprovaline (1) Dylovene (1)
───────────────────────────────────────
[head=3]ADVANCED MEDICATIONS (AFTER CORE STOCK)[/head]

[color=#ff3636][bold]NO MORE SMASH[/bold][/color] — Severe Blunt Trauma | Dose: 10u  
- Reagents: [bold]Lithium (27) | Sugar (30) | Bicaridine (30)[/bold]

[color=#b9bf93][bold]HOW TO PATCH A CHEESE[/bold][/color] — Piercing | Dose: 11u  
- Reagents: [bold]HYDROXY (50%) | Bicaridine (50%)[/bold]

[color=#283332][bold]KNIFE AWARENESS[/bold][/color] — Slash / Cut Trauma | Dose: 12u  
- Reagents: [bold]BENZENE (50%) | Bicaridine (50%)[/bold]

[color=#ff7db5][bold]MY EX HEARTH[/bold][/color] — Cold / Rapid Temperature | Advanced  
- Step 1: [bold]Iron (1) | Silicon (1)[/bold], heat → Fersilicite  
- Step 2: [bold]Copper (2) | Plasma (1)[/bold]  
- Notes: Rapid cooling / hypothermia

───────────────────────────────────────
[head=3]SUPPORT CHEMICALS[/head]

Advice: Use **saline** instead of bloodpacks to save resources; birds cannot process saline, so reserve blood only for avian patients.  

[color=#0064C8][bold]SALINE[/bold][/color] — Blood Replacement / Hydration  
- Reagents: [bold]Chlorine (1) | Sodium (1) | Water (8)[/bold]  
- Notes: Standard patients receive saline; birds receive blood

[color=#ffffff][bold]HYDROXY[/bold][/color] — Base Reagent for PUNC  
- Reagents: [bold]Hydrogen (1) | Oxygen (1)[/bold]  
- Notes: Mixed 1:1 with Bicaridine → HOW TO PATCH A CHEESE (11u)

[color=#ffffff][bold]BENZENE[/bold][/color] — Base Reagent for LACERINOL  
- Reagents: [bold]Carbon (1) | Hydrogen (1)[/bold]  
- Notes: Mixed 1:1 with Bicaridine → KNIFE AWARENESS (11u)

───────────────────────────────────────
Sincerely,  
Brig Medical Chemistry Reference
